Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT! Joe Root has snatched the ball out of thin air and it needed something spectacular from England to break this stubborn partnership! What an exhibition of fast bowling this has been and Mark Wood bowls yet another peach. This is bowled on a good length and angled in from outside off. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend the line of the ball but it straightens a touch after pitching. Takes the outside edge and flies into the gap between the wicketkeeper and first slip. Joe Root stretches his left hand out and grabs the ball as it looks to have passed him. His teammates are absolutely thrilled with the blinder he has taken and Australia lose their second wicket.
Default_Commentary: 42.5: Mark Wood to Marnus Labuschagne, OUT! c Joe Root b Mark Wood.
Howout: c Joe Root b Mark Wood

Commentary: OUT! PLUMB! Stuart Broad gets his man right after the break and Usman Khawaja's long vigil comes to an end! It is remarkable how Stuart Broad can do this consistently over the years as he once again gets a crucial wicket for his side. This is bowled full and into the stumps. Usman Khawaja is stuck in the crease and misses his block as the ball goes onto rap against the pads. The bowler goes up in appeal instantly and the batter has a worried look on his face. The umpire finally raises his finger and after some consultation, Usman Khawaja goes upstairs for the review. UltraEdge shows there is no bat involved and Ball Tracking has three reds. Stuart Broad gets his 150th Ashes wicket and Australia are three wickets down.
Default_Commentary: 51.5: Stuart Broad to Usman Khawaja, OUT! lbw b Stuart Broad.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Stuart Broad gets two wickets in two overs and he has turned the tie in favour of England right after Lunch with a remarkable spell of fast bowling! Commentary: Almost a disaster for Australia! This is on a good length and on middle. Steven Smith tucks it with soft hands towards deep square leg and comes back for the second, but stumbles a bit when he turns. The substitute fielder George Ealham comes running in from deep and releases a quick throw at the batter's end where Jonny Bairstow takes the bails off in a flash with Smith putting in a desperate dive. The first replay shows that Smith is short of the crease and England players start celebrating. However, the third umpire asks for another angle where we can see that Bairstow breaks the stumps before collecting the ball but the bails are still on top, and when they are removed Smith is inside the crease. A lucky escape for Smith!

Commentary: OUT! LBW! England finally get a breakthrough and it is Chris Woakes who strikes for the hosts claiming his thrid wicket! Todd Murphy's enterprising inning comes to an end and Australia are now nine wickets down. This is bowled on a good length and angled into the stumps from outside off. Todd Murphy looks to defend but gets beaten on the inside edge and the ball goes onto hit him flush on the pads. The bowler goes up in appeal instantly and the umpire raises his finger after some thought. Todd Murphy goes upstairs for the review and UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Ball Tracking has umpires call on wickets hitting and the onfield decision stands.
Default_Commentary: 101.2: Chris Woakes to Todd Murphy, OUT! lbw b Chris Woakes.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT! Ben Stokes shows remarkable composure at the boundary and pulls off a remarkable catch! Joe Root is rewarded with his second wicket and Australia's inning comes to an end having taken a lead of 12 runs. Joe Root floats this one full and in line with the stumps. Pat Cummins looks to make room and clears his front foot out of the way. Heaves the ball towards the long on fence where Ben Stokes is standing right at the ropes. He leaps up and grabs hold of the ball but the momentum is taking him over the boundary. He flings the ball into the air before landing and steps back into the field of play to complete a very difficult catch. England would have liked to wrap up this inning earlier but they have managed to do so just at the stroke of STUMPS on DAY 2!
Default_Commentary: 103.1: Joe Root to Pat Cummins, OUT! c Ben Stokes b Joe Root.
Howout: c Ben Stokes b Joe Root

Commentary: James Anderson survives a close call and England have not been bowled out yet! Todd Murphy flights this full and in line with the stumps. England's number eleven adopts the reverse sweep once again but skims his bat against the turf and does not connect with the ball. It hits him on his forearm in front of the stumps and the Australians are convinced that this is out! The umpire agrees and raises his finger but James Anderson opts for the review. UltraEdge confirms there is no bat involved and Ball Tracking indicates that the ball is going over the stumps. England still nine wickets down as James Anderson survives.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! Todd Murphy gets his fourth of the game and England's innings has come to an end within two overs of Day 4! Todd Murphy loops this one full and pitching just outside off. The ball comes into the stumps with the angle as James Anderson goes for the reverse sweep once again. He does not connect this time and the ball hits him on his pad. A loud appeal from the bowler and the umpire takes a long time before raising his finger. James Anderson goes for the review and replays show that the ball is quite far from the bat. Ball Tracking has umpires call on wickets hitting and the on-field decision stands. England have been bowled out for 395 and Stuart Broad remains unbeaten in his last Test inning as the set the visitors a target of 384.
Default_Commentary: 81.5: Todd Murphy to James Anderson, OUT! lbw b Todd Murphy.
Howout: lbw b Todd Murphy

Commentary: Now then, what has happened here? Tossed up, turning in, on middle, Steven Smith lunges forward to defend. The ball lobs off the gloves of Smith and goes towards leg slip. Ben Stokes times the jump to perfection and takes a one-handed stunner. However, as he went to celebrate, his palm hit his knee and the ball popped out. England think they have got Steven Smith caught at leg slip but Ben Stokes does not seem convinced. He still goes for the review though. The third umpire deems that Stokes was not in control of the catch and adjudges it as not out. Boos ring around the Kennington Oval and the English players are bemused as well.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT! Moeen Ali gets his first wicket of the game and it may be a huge scalp in the context of the game! Travis Head's attacking ability could have taken the game away from the hosts in a jiffy but he perishes 7 runs short of his half-century. Moeen Ali flights this one full and outside the off stump. Travis Head goes for the expansive drive through covers but the ball lands on the rough and turns away from the bat sharply. Takes the outside edge of the bat and goes towards slip where Joe Root makes the catch look really easy. Australia lose their fourth wicket early in the final session and England will have their tails up as they look for a few more quick wickets.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Three wickets in three consecutive overs and the game has turned in a flash! Australia are absolutely crumbling here and it is England who are right on top in this tie! Moeen Ali has two quick wickets and he was bound to make an impact on this game despite his injury! This is tossed up full and outside the off stump. Mitchell Marsh pushes forward to defend and the ball takes the inside edge while spinning back towards the stumps. It goes on to hit the pads and lobs up to the right of the wicketkeeper. Jonny Bairstow sticks his hand out and grabs the ball as he falls over but does not let his elbow hit the ground. Mitchell Marsh does not even wait for the umpire to decide as he turns around and begins his walk back to the pavilion. Australia have lost six wickets now and England are four scalps away from leveling the series!

Commentary: OUT! EDGED AND GONE! There it is, a fairytale ending to Stuart Broad's career! Broad nips out Carey and makes him the final victim of his career! Serves it on a good length, in the channel on off, angling in this time, from 'round the wicket, Alex Carey looks to get on the front foot and gets his bat out in front to defend. The ball nibbles away after pitching and does the trick for Broad. Catches the outside edge and Jonny Bairstow behind the wickets does the rest. Stuart Broad is delighted and so are his teammates. The Oval crowd is up on their feet to applaud what has been a magnificent career. England win by 49 runs!
